<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 17 日星期一 04:09:05 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Most Shocking Aspect of RFK Jr.’s Anti-Semitism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>令人惊讶的不是肯尼迪提出了反犹太阴谋，而是花了这么长时间。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rxpGHPhlsK812tEHTXc5twzmss8=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rfk_illo_horz/original.jpg" alt="小罗伯特·RFK" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：杰米·麦卡锡/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>上周，在曼哈顿的一次晚宴上，民主党初选候选人小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪分享了他对冠状病毒本质的直率想法。 “有一种观点认为它是针对种族的，”他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/15/rfk-jr-says-covid-was-ethnically-targeted-to-spare-jews/">在视频中的</a>言论中解释道。 “COVID-19 的目标是攻击白人和黑人。免疫力最强的人是德系犹太人和中国人。”肯尼迪补充道，可以肯定的是，“我们不知道它是否是故意针对的。”换句话说，肯尼迪显然认为，这场大流行病是否是由一个阴暗的阴谋集团为了拯救中国和犹太人而策划的，这是一个悬而未决的问题。<br><br>中国至少有 100 万人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/02/china-million-covid-deaths-communist-party/673177/">死于</a>COVID-19；纽约等地的犹太人非但没有对这种病毒免疫，反而常常被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bklyner.com/editorial-stop-blaming-orthodox-jews-blame-trump-for-brooklyn-covid-spikes/">不公平地指责</a>为传播病毒的罪魁祸首。作为一名曾与冠状病毒作斗争的犹太人，肯尼迪的说法对我来说是新闻。但考虑到消息来源，他们也并不感到意外。这是因为肯尼迪是一个阴谋论者，而阴谋的弧线很短，并且向犹太人倾斜。<br><br>以下只是肯尼迪<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-jr-2024-election-anti-establishment-voters/674588/">观点</a>的一小部分：无线互联网的辐射<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D3OkKer7Ohw">会导致</a>癌症；供水中的化学物质正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/13/politics/robert-kennedy-jr-chemicals-water-children-frogs/index.html">造成性别不安</a>；中央情报局杀害了他的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-interview-david-samuels#:~:text=he%20was%20also%20a%20CIA%20asset">父亲</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/3993563-robert-kennedy-jr-sees-overwhelming-evidence-cia-involved-in-jfk-assassination/">叔叔</a>约翰·F·肯尼迪总统；抗抑郁药<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/robert-kennedy-jr-elon-musk-american-revolution-twitter-spaces-conversation-2023-6">导致了</a>今天的大规模枪击事件；乔治·W·布什 (George W. Bush) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://clevelandmagazine.com/in-the-cle/politics/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-nut-job">窃取了</a>2004 年总统选举的胜利；你手机的 5G 连接是“收集我们的数据并控制我们的行为” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2022/01/23/rfk-jr-compares-pandemic-mandates-to-nazi-germany/">阴谋的一部分</a>。<br><br>从肯尼迪的职业生涯来看，令人惊讶的不是他涉足反犹太主义，而是他花了这么长时间才到达这里。正如我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">之前写过的</a>：<br><br><p>反犹太主义可以说是世界上<a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/texas-synagogue-anti-semitism-conspiracy-theory/621286/">最古老、最持久的</a>阴谋论。它将犹太人描绘成世界政治、经济和社会问题背后幕后操纵的傀儡师。对于那些寻求简单解决生活复杂问题的人来说，这种观点提供了现成的解释——也是敌人。任何寻求社会苦难单一来源的人可能会从普通的阴谋论开始，但很快就会以人云亦云的反犹太思想告终。</p>因为反犹太主义已经产生了几个世纪以来将人类问题归咎于犹太人的材料，所以一个相信有一只看不见的手在操纵世界事务的人最终会发现它属于一个看不见的犹太人。<br><br>因此，在阴谋论边缘流通而不遭遇反犹太主义是不可能的。这就是为什么肯尼迪经常发现自己与那些相信并表达反犹太思想的人在一起。上周，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1678528085258301440">大肆宣传</a>自己与说唱歌手艾斯·库珀(Ice Cube)的会面，艾斯·库珀是一位阴谋论者， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/ice-cube-criticized-anti-semitic-images-conspiracy-theories-9400472/">长期以来</a>一直发表奇怪的反犹太主义推文和歌词。过去，肯尼迪还与仇恨传教士路易斯·法拉罕（Louis Farrakhan）达成了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LouisFarrakhan/status/614862836431392769">共同</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4910041/user-clip-rfk-jr-told-louis-farrakhan-cdc-kill-black-boys">目标</a>，后者经常谴责所谓的犹太人控制媒体和政府。<br><br>肯尼迪最终会回应他的阴谋集团的反犹太主义假设是不可避免的。事实上，他远非第一个走上从阴谋主义到彻底反犹太主义这条老路的人。近年来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/61897999d581bf0020f74c32/why-rep-marjorie-taylor-greene-just-championed-louis-farrakhan/">马乔里·泰勒·格林</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/why-its-become-harder-to-joke-about-anti-semitism/672120/">凯里·欧文</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">埃隆·马斯克</a>等形形色色的人已经从普通的阴谋论发展到反犹太论点。就连肯尼迪的 COVID-19 猜想的内容也不是原创的：几个世纪以来，犹太人一直被指责传播瘟疫，最著名的是欧洲<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/the-black-death">黑死病</a>期间。<br><br>周末，肯尼迪在推特上愤怒地发布了否认和澄清， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1680227322509635595">坚称</a>他的意思只是说新冠病毒“作为针对种族的生物武器的一种概念证明”，而不是“种族效应是故意设计的”，尽管他明确提出他原来的言论中确实有这种可能性。<br><br>肯尼迪本人没有反犹太主义历史，也从未表现出对犹太人的个人偏见。但他的阴谋罗盘确保了他最终会到达这个目的地，因为它只指向一个方向。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 17:36:04 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[In Vilnius, NATO Got Two Wins and One Big Loss]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>北约终于有了一个计划。不幸的是，它不包括承认乌克兰。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Ee9GpeoagNiAOsJtTyM-cPXsnUM=/0x183:4000x2433/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1528741260/original.jpg" alt="乌克兰总统泽连斯基在维尔纽斯举行的北约会议新闻发布会上发表讲话。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>阿图尔·维达克/NurPhoto/Getty</figcaption></figure>北约维尔纽斯峰会发生了三件重要的事情：一次突破、一次鲜为人知但影响巨大的成功以及一次失望。突破在于土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安最终同意瑞典加入。这次峰会最重要的成果是批准了 4000 多页的军事计划，用于北约国家的实际防御。令人失望的是乌克兰没有获得加入北约的途径。<br><br>这一突破成为会议早期的头条新闻。埃尔多安总统几个月来一直阻止瑞典加入，要求瑞典<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-must-do-more-if-it-wants-to-join-nato-turkey-says-f00b73b3?mod=article_inline">引渡约 120 名</a>被指控的库尔德工人党 (PKK) 活动人士和葛兰主义者（美国也为此与土耳其发生争执）；解除对土耳其的武器禁运；并通过更友好的反恐立法、“防止挑衅的机制”，甚至修改宪法。土耳其就其中大部分措施做出了承诺。但随后，在峰会前夕，埃尔多安<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/10/world/europe/erdogan-turkey-sweden-nato.html">又提出了另一个</a>先决条件：土耳其加入欧盟。幸运的是，有点令人惊讶的是，埃尔多安同意北约秘书长延斯·斯托尔滕贝格的交易，其中显然包括与总统乔·拜登的双边会晤、美国向土耳其交付 F-16 战斗机以及设立北约“反恐特别协调员” ”。<br><br>但对于埃尔多安来说， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/12/world/europe/erdogan-turkey-sweden-nato.html">一切都还没有结束</a>，我们可能还会看到另一轮谈判，因为瑞典法院现在（在协议宣布后） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2023/7/13/swedens-supreme-court-blocks-extradition-of-two-wanted-by-turkey">阻止了引渡</a>，而土耳其议会将在接下来的两个月内不会开会，所以是时候提出更多要求了。<br><br>维尔纽斯会议的巨大成功是通过了一项全面计划，以履行北约的基本责任——保卫其成员国的领土。该联盟自 1991 年以来就没有这样的计划。为了消除俄罗斯对将北约成员国的安全范围扩大到前华沙条约组织和前苏联国家的担忧， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thehill.com/opinion/international/3514801-nato-russia-its-time-to-suspend-the-founding-act/">北约声称</a>没有理由在该地区部署核武器或大量作战部队。新成员国。这一承诺取决于安全环境，随着俄罗斯对乌克兰的侵略，安全环境发生了巨大变化。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/nato-jens-stoltenberg-unelected-bureaucrat-ukraine/674608/">安妮·阿普尔鲍姆：多边人比普京意识到的更强大</a><br><br>在维尔纽斯通过的新计划长达<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.economist.com/international/2023/07/02/nato-is-drafting-new-plans-to-defend-europe">4,000 页</a>，这证明了其严肃性，并且北约国家政府已同意这些计划。它们允许北约军事指挥官向不同国家的部队分配特定的义务，从而在北约盟国受到攻击时促进有效的共同防御。这一安排锁定了美国及其欧洲盟国之间的责任分担，这些盟国需要通过增加军费开支以及提供自己的太空和网络资产来减少对华盛顿的依赖。<br><br>联合战争是一项微妙而艰巨的任务。提前了解盟国愿意做什么，以及他们的部队力量在哪里可以最好地满足需求，将使那些最容易受到俄罗斯潜在侵略的盟国放心，并提高所有盟国共同有效行动的能力。北约为这些计划设计、同意并拨出资源这一事实应该有助于阻止对其前线国家的攻击。<br><br>然而，维尔纽斯会议的结束却令人失望。距离俄罗斯入侵乌克兰已经过去了500多天。尽管美国和英国向乌克兰提供了武器和合作，但它们未能充分履行根据 1994 年《布达佩斯备忘录》所做出的确保乌克兰安全的承诺，以换取乌克兰放弃其核武库。与此同时，基辅一直在推动寻找加入北约的明确道路。乌克兰<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/06/03/1179979756/zelenskyy-accepts-ukraine-cannot-become-a-nato-member-until-the-war-ends">承认</a>，当该国仍处于战争状态时，不可能成为该国的成员（尽管北约过去已经找到了解决该问题的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.iiss.org/online-analysis/survival-online/2023/072/how-to-end-a-war-some-historical-lessons-for-ukraine/">创造性解决方案</a>），但希望得到承诺，一旦战争结束，它将成为该国的成员。相反，拜登总统在维尔纽斯会议之前表示， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/09/politics/joe-biden-ukraine-nato-russia-cnntv/index.html">乌克兰尚未准备好</a>加入北约。<br><br>乌克兰总统泽连斯基被激怒了。面对国家安全顾问杰克·沙利文和英国国防部长本·华莱士的断然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ft.com/content/dc658252-6acd-44fc-8e0c-51a284009762?shareType=nongift">拒绝</a>，他发布了一条<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/ZelenskyyUa/status/1678707674811187200">愤怒的</a>推文；后者建议乌克兰应该对所给予的所有支持表示感谢。<br><br>北约国家确实大力支持乌克兰，但让安全的人们告诉那些受到攻击的人应该感激是不恰当的。拜登政府不公平地希望从其宽泛的言辞中受益——美国总统承诺“只要需要”就支持乌克兰，让乌克兰赢得战争——但又不想因其在乌克兰急需的武器问题上做出的胆怯决定而受到批评。 。例如，华盛顿仍在保留陆军战术导弹系统等远程弹药，其<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2023/07/12/biden-vilnius-nato-ukraine/">政策</a>的驱动力被<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em>描述为“坚信美国在乌克兰的失误可能引发第三次世界大战”。<br><br>拜登总统担心直接卷入战争的风险并没有错，他在将北约第五条安全保障扩展到与俄罗斯交战的国家方面也吝啬也没有错。但政府通过有效贬低乌克兰所做的一切来捍卫这些选择，无论在道义上还是在实践上都是错误的。拜登总统将美国从阿富汗撤军的失败归咎于阿富汗安全部队，而不是我们自己的政策，随意否认乌克兰加入北约的意愿，感觉就像是一回事。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2022/05/ukraine-russia-nato-jens-stoltenberg-interview/661140/">阅读：“我们不要忘记暴行，这一点极其重要”</a><br><br>北约成员资格的标准一直是主观的。 1952年希腊和土耳其入盟后发生军事政变时，他们是主观的； 1955年，分裂的德国西半部被接纳； 1982年，正在实行民主化的西班牙被接纳。根据地缘战略环境，制定并放宽了更为苛刻的标准，这些地缘战略环境为乌克兰最终的入盟提供了更鼓舞士气的前景。<br><br>失去冷静是泽连斯基在这场战争中为数不多的外交失误之一，他很快就纠正了这一错误。这位乌克兰总统<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/ZelenskyyUa/status/1679260450263818240">随后的言论</a>让人想起<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://history.state.gov/milestones/1937-1945/atlantic-conf">1941年会议</a>后温斯顿·丘吉尔的言论，当时英国希望但没有得到美国承诺打击纳粹德国：比以往任何时候都更接近，不是是否会这样，而是何时。<br><br>在北约峰会召开的同时，七国集团发表声明称，成员国将开始与乌克兰就双边安全安排进行谈判。它的目的是低于北约的承诺，但也比什么都没有。但该组织的承诺只是开始讨论——讨论那些不愿通过北约做出安全承诺的国家，以及那些未能履行其向北约做出的承诺的国家的承诺。乌克兰，1994 年。<br><br>对乌克兰继续被排除在北约之外的最好掩饰是，拜登白宫将明年举行的北约 75 周年峰会推迟了实际周年纪念日四个月，并且距离 2024 年总统大选更近，以便在政治上掀起欢迎乌克兰加入的浪潮。北约大家庭在对总统具有最大政治价值的时刻。希望白宫的政治人物不像国家安全团队那么胆怯。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 15:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/vilnius-nato-summit-sweden-turkey-ukraine/674721/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/vilnius-nato-summit-sweden-turkey-ukraine/674721/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Goodbye to the Prophets of Doom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>关于全球经济的传统观点是富人越来越富，穷人越来越穷。如果事实并非如此怎么办？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AAP-a5AsFwsWVsmF4hkep4tT-TU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/inequality_2/original.jpg" alt="一张美元钞票被折皱得像楼梯的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>在大衰退<span class="smallcaps">期间</span>，公众对经济的讨论经历了极大的失望。<br><br>在这个国家的大部分历史中，大多数美国人都认为未来会给他们或他们的后代带来更大的富裕。尽管经济危机时有发生，但总的情况似乎是每个阶层的人都在进步。这些期望在很大程度上得到了证实：例如，在 20 世纪中叶的大部分时间里，美国工薪阶层所享有的生活水平远远高于一两代人之前的富裕美国人所享有的生活水平。<br><br>但2008年金融危机之后，一段时期的严重经济困难以及经济学家对不平等话题的新兴趣颠覆了这些假设。经济衰退的预测占据了话题。美国这个长期以来以其根深蒂固的乐观主义而闻名的国家，开始对未来感到恐惧——现在看来，大多数人拥有的东西会越来越少。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/inflation-jobs-unemployment-recession/674593/">Adam Ozimek：差点引发经济衰退的简单错误</a><br><br>三个论点为“大失望”提供了思想基础。第一个由麻省理工学院经济学家戴维·奥托提出的颇具影响力的观点是，大多数美国人的工资在人们的记忆中第一次出现停滞。尽管在上个世纪的大部分时间里，美国人的平均收入大约每代人翻一番，但大多数人的工资增长在 20 世纪 80 年代开始趋于平稳。到 2010 年，较贫穷的美国人似乎面临着一个生活水平不再能得到任何真正改善的未来。<br><br>第二个论点与全球化对全球收入分配的影响有关。在一张后来被称为“大象曲线”的图表中，塞尔维亚裔美国经济学家布兰科·米兰诺维奇认为，世界上最贫穷的人只经历了很小的收入增长；中间百分位数从全球化中受益匪浅；那些中上层阶级——包括美国等富裕国家的许多产业工人和服务业人员——的收入停滞不前；最富有的人像强盗一样亲热。全球化似乎是一件喜忧参半的事情，而且对于美国等工业化经济体的底层工薪阶层来说，这显然是一件令人担忧的事情。<br><br>最后也是最全面的争论是关于不平等的性质和原因。尽管大部分人口刚刚维持繁荣，但最富有的美国人的财富和收入却在迅速增长。法国经济学家托马斯·皮凯蒂在 2013 年出人意料的畅销书<i>《二十一世纪的资本》</i>中提出，这种趋势可能会持续下去。皮凯蒂认为，资本的回报早已超过了劳动力的回报，他似乎暗示，只有像一场重大战争这样的灾难性事件——或者似乎不会出现的激进的政治转型——才能帮助遏制这种趋势。不平等现象日益严重。<br><br>巨大的失望继续影响着许多美国人对当前和未来经济状况的看法。但随着大流行和通货膨胀的上升改变了世界经济，这篇论文的知识基础已经开始动摇。经济悲观主义的理由开始看起来不再像以前那样令人信服。是时候修改“大失望”的核心原则了吗？<br><br>作为美国最著名的劳动经济学家<span class="smallcaps">之一</span>，奥托尔在过去十年中提供了有关美国工人收入停滞的大量证据，特别是对于那些没有大学学位的工人。<br><br>奥特尔在 2010 年一篇极具影响力的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hamiltonproject.org/publication/policy-proposal/the-polarization-of-job-opportunities-in-the-u-s-labor-market-implications-for-employment-and-earnings/">论文</a>中写道，美国经济正在出现分化。尽管对高技能工人的需求上升，但对“中等工资、中等技能的白领和蓝领工作”的需求却在萎缩。美国经济曾经提供了大量的中产阶级就业机会，现在正分裂为一个非常富裕的专业阶层和一个变得更加贫困的剩余阶层。奥托尔表示，总体结果是“非大学工人的实际收入下降”和“工资不平等急剧加剧”。<br><br>奥托过去对美国劳动力主要部分工资下降的研究使他现在听起来更加乐观，这一点更加值得注意。奥托在今年早些时候发表的一份<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://economics.mit.edu/sites/default/files/2023-03/The%20Unexpected%20Compression%20-%20Competition%20at%20Work%20in%20the%20Low%20Wage%20Labor%20Market.pdf">工作论文</a>中指出，由于公司在疫情末期拼命寻找工人，低薪工人发现自己处于更好的讨价还价地位。经济命运发生了显着逆转。<br><br> “分布底部不成比例的工资增长降低了大学工资溢价，并将自 1980 年以来总体工资不平等的上升趋势扭转了约四分之一，”奥托尔写道。近期经济趋势的大赢家正是那些在过去几十年中被排除在外的群体：“40岁以下且没有大学学位的工人的工资上涨尤其强劲。”<br><br>奥托尔表示，即使考虑到通货膨胀因素，美国底层四分之一工人的收入多年来首次出现显着增长。这位之前曾写过美国劳动力“两极分化”的学者现在得出的结论是，美国经济正在经历“意外的压缩”。换句话说，贫富差距正在以惊人的速度缩小。<br><br>一位<span class="smallcaps">作家并不是</span>唯一一位对大失望的基础产生怀疑的主要经济学家。米拉诺维奇认为，他的“大象曲线”之所以如此有影响力，部分原因是它证实了许多人对全球化影响的担忧。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.socialeurope.eu/global-income-inequality-time-to-revise-the-elephant">他现在承认</a>，他著名的图表是“对许多人想法的实证证实”。他对那条传统智慧不再那么确定了。<br><br>几年前，米兰诺维奇开始更新最初的大象曲线，该曲线基于 1988 年至 2008 年的数据。结果令人震惊——一个积极的结果。一旦 Milanovic 将下一个十年的数据纳入到 2018 年，曲线的形状就发生了变化。这条曲线的病毒性名称不再是“上升、下降、再上升”的特征，而是稳步下降的梯度现在似乎描绘了一幅简单且乐观得多的图景。在他现在调查的四十年里，世界上最贫穷的人的收入增长得非常快，中间分布的人的收入增长得相当快，而最富有的人的收入则相当缓慢。几乎每个人的全球经济状况都在改善，而且与传统观点相反，获得最大回报的是最贫困的人，而不是最富裕的人。<br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foreignaffairs.com/world/great-convergence-equality-branko-milanovic"><i>《外交事务》</i>最近发表的一篇文章</a>中，米兰诺维奇走得更远。 “我们经常被告知，”他写道，“我们生活在一个不平等的时代。”但当你查看最新的全球数据时，你会发现这是错误的：事实上，“世界正变得比 100 多年来更加平等。”<br><br><span class="smallcaps">直到今天</span>，皮凯蒂仍然是大失望的守护神。没有哪个思想家比他更频繁地被援引来证明这一理论的合理性。但即便是皮凯蒂十年前做出的悲观诊断，现在看起来也没有那么可怕了。<br><br>部分原因是皮凯蒂的研究受到了其他经济学家的批评。根据一种有影响力的论点，皮凯蒂错误地理解了为什么二战后几十年里许多工业化国家的资本回报率高于劳动力回报率。皮凯蒂认为，如果没有一致的压力来阻止这种情况发生，资本主义的本质将永远有利于亿万富翁和大公司，而不是普通工人。但根据西北大学经济学家马修·罗尼利 (Matthew Rognlie) 的说法，皮凯蒂对此的解释<i> </i>在此期间，不平等现象的加剧是由于对数据的误解。<br><br>罗格利认为，20 世纪下半叶资本回报率过高的主要原因是巴黎和纽约等大都市中心房价的大幅上涨。如果这一时期的资本回报率高于劳动回报率，那么原因不是一般的经济趋势，而是特定的政治因素，例如限制性的建筑规范。此外，主要的受益者并不是皮凯蒂所关注的亿万富翁和大企业，而是他们的利益。相反，他们是中上层专业人士，拥有大城市的大部分住房。<br><br>经济学家们仍在争论这些批评是否切中要害。但就在皮凯蒂为自己的工作辩护的同时，他本人也开始对经济的长期结构表现出更加乐观的态度。在他 2022 年出版的著作<i>《平等简史》</i>中，他将不平等的加剧视为一种异常现象。 “至少自十八世纪末以来，出现了一场争取平等的历史性运动，”他写道。 “2020 年代的世界，无论看起来多么不公正，都比 1950 年或 1900 年的世界更加平等，而后者本身在许多方面都比 1850 年或 1780 年的世界更加平等。”<br><br>与奥托尔和米拉诺维奇一样，皮凯蒂似乎也得出结论，“大失望”的论点在关键方面是错误的。<br><br>现在就消除对收入停滞或不平等加剧的担忧<span class="smallcaps">还为时过早</span>。三位前末日预言家都强调社会和政治因素在塑造经济结果中所发挥的作用。因此，他们认为最近较贫穷的美国人的工资增长部分是由唐纳德·特朗普和乔·拜登为应对这一流行病而推行的扩张性经济政策造成的。<br><br>同样，世界上一些最贫困人口近几十年来所取得的巨大成就部分归功于其政府利用产业政策来塑造全球化对其国家影响的努力。正如皮凯蒂所说，从长远来看，资本回报是否会超过劳动力回报，取决于有关税收和再分配、工会实力和劳动力市场规则的政治决策。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/labor-shortage-low-unemployment-inflation/674263/">奥伦·卡斯：劳动力短缺的神话</a><br><br>最近关于我们经济前景的好消息不应让我们得出可能很快就会变得过于乐观的结论。但我们也应该避免使本能的悲观主义持续下去，这种悲观主义看起来越来越没有根据。尽管悲观主义可能看起来很聪明或精明，但对我们建设更美好世界的集体能力的愤世嫉俗只会让我们更难为创造未来所需的经济政策赢得支持。<br><br>进步主义者有时似乎相信，他们可以通过让未来看起来可怕来动员人们。但当选民感到受到威胁时，通常是不择手段的反动派做出不切实际的承诺，并把受益的局外人当作替罪羊。工资停滞和不平等加剧仍然是我们必须保持警惕的真正危险，但更美好的经济未来看起来更容易实现这一事实应该值得大肆庆祝。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Delivery Apps Just Did the Impossible]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>硅谷正在用自己的游戏打败多米诺骨牌。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AGu-O9jBTio589Oh61_Rq-CVEfE=/0x0:5337x3002/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_492047870/original.jpg" alt="顶部带有多米诺骨牌标志的送货车" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>丹尼尔·阿克/彭博/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>近年来，达美乐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">有时</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">自诩为</a>一家以送<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">披萨</a>为副业的科技公司。这是真的。通过改进人工智能、GPS、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/06/17/dominos-will-start-delivering-pizzas-via-an-autonomous-robot-this-fall/">自动驾驶汽车</a>和增强现实等技术，全球最大的披萨连锁店将送餐这一黑暗艺术变成了一门科学。这一切都始于其著名的 Pizza Tracker，该产品于 2008 年推出，并创建了跟踪食品配送的早期标准。 Domino&#39;s 现在有大约<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">15 种不同的</a>披萨订购<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">方式</a>，包括语音助手、Facebook Messenger、Slack 和一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/4283913/dominos-zero-click-ordering-app/">“零点击”应用程序</a>，可在 10 秒后自动为您订购。<br><br>所有这些技术帮助达美乐增加了销售额并简化了运营，使其最终<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/25/why-pizza-hut-is-struggling-to-against-dominos-and-papa-johns.html">“超越了小屋披萨”</a> ，成为美国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">约</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">三分之一</a>披萨外卖的服务商。其他餐厅，无论是披萨店还是其他餐厅，都已经开始依赖一系列第三方应用程序，而达美乐则将一切都保留在内部，这意味着它处于领先地位 - 从理论上讲，您也是如此。没有邮递员，没问题：只需<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dominos.com/en/pages/order/#!/checkout/">9.99 美元左右</a>，加上少量费用和小费，多米诺 (Domino) 司机就会送出一份达美乐 (Domino) 披萨，30 分钟内就会送到您家门口。<br><br>但本周早些时候，达美乐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">宣布</a>它也将与一款送货应用程序合作。到 2023 年底，大多数地方的饥饿群众将能够通过 Uber Eats 订购达美乐 (Domino) 馅饼和各种钠炸弹（尽管达美乐 (Domino) 的司机仍将送餐）。通过与 Uber 联手，该公司承认 DoorDash、Uber Eats 和 Grubhub 等外卖应用程序已成为主导地位——使用它们已接近餐厅维持生计的必要要求。如果 Domino&#39;s 都无法摆脱送货应用程序，那么还有谁可以呢？<br><br>恰如其分的是，美国的送餐热潮实际上是从达美乐开始的。该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/27/business/pizza-s-home-delivery-war.html">经常被认为</a>推广了披萨外卖的概念（ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">它</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">创造了现代披萨盒</a>，联合创始人汤姆·莫纳汉甚至在送披萨时<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/19/the-deliverer">遇见了他的妻子</a>）。尽管披萨订购从固定电话和手机转向通过移动应用程序拨号，但以送货为中心的多米诺骨牌模式却拥有惊人的寿命。 2011 年，时任首席执行官帕特里克·多伊尔 (Patrick Doyle) 开始了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://pizzaturnaround.com/">一场不太可能的全国性广告活动，</a>承认他的披萨有点糟糕，不久后，他向他的技术团队<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncr.com/blogs/restaurants/digital-innovations-dominos">发出了挑战</a>：他希望订购披萨变得足够简单，以便有人可以在等待时完成。在红绿灯处。移动点餐是未来，未来，披萨点餐只需 17 秒。<br><br>从某种意义上说，达美乐已经成为其自身成功的受害者。该公司的技术悟性帮助公众做好了不仅仅是披萨外卖的准备。这些第三方应用程序出现在 2010 年代零工经济繁荣时期，然后在疫情早期爆发。随着疫情放缓，食品配送销售本可以重蹈 Peloton 的覆辙，但<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/pages/consumer-business/articles/future-of-restaurants-study.html">事实并非如此</a>。去年，大约 14% 的披萨销量是通过外卖应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">完成的</a>，此外还有一系列让餐厅菜单看起来平淡无奇的菜肴和菜肴。截至 2023 年，数十万家餐厅都使用了外卖应用，提供高级餐厅的干式熟成牛排和麦当劳的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">干式牛排百吉饼</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">。</a>餐厅的餐厅可能会再次爆满，但这些应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://secondmeasure.com/datapoints/food-delivery-services-grubhub-uber-eats-doordash-postmates/">现在带来的收入比以往任何时候都多</a>。<br><br>换句话说，它们已经变得太大而不容忽视。尽管达美乐将继续提供自己的披萨，但其首席执行官拉塞尔·韦纳 (Russell Weiner) 在讨论 Uber Eats 优食交易时，用简单的语言<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.restaurantbusinessonline.com/financing/dominos-uber-eats-deal-acknowledges-reality-third-party-marketplace">表达了错过的成本</a>：“聚合平台上发生了 50 亿美元的披萨销售额……[那]我们应该有三分之一。”<br><br>随着数以百万计的餐厅员工准备订单和数以百万计的零工为他们送货，整个送餐生态系统已经合并，这对餐厅和整个餐饮文化都产生了巨大的影响。这些应用程序可以向餐厅收取<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">高达</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">30% 的</a>费用，这给利润本来就很紧张的企业带来了沉重的负担，需要大量的订单量才能实现收支平衡。他们拥有如此大的权力，以至于他们现在正在影响<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://get.grubhub.com/blog/delivery-menu-tips/">餐馆的菜单</a>，有时即使你在里面用餐。与此同时，承担所有这些职能的送货员仍然作为独立承包商获得低工资，没有任何保护或讨价还价的能力。<br><br>对于食客来说，将科技进一步引入餐饮业是有成本的。根据 2021 年的一份报告，送餐应用程序与社交媒体巨头<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/social-media-and-food-delivery-apps-sell-the-most-personal-data">并驾齐驱</a>，成为消费者个人数据的最大收集者和兜售者。多米诺<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">自己承认</a>，Uber 愿意交出客户数据是其决定与该公司达成协议的关键因素。即使在沙发上订购任何东西变得更加容易和方便，外卖应用程序将继续迫使餐厅调整其运营以适应他们的需求。无论您每天晚上都订购送货服务还是根本没有使用过应用程序，这一点都很重要。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why YIMBY Righteousness Backfires]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>将郊区居民视为可恨的势利小人并不会让他们更欢迎新来者。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/owUJAAHGITBEG0A2viEAgvjioqE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/YIMBY/original.jpg" alt="加利福尼亚州安提阿的郊区房屋" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>杰森·亨利 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure>如果想要生活在一个主要居民能够轻松负担过高房价的田园社区是错误的，那么大多数美国人也不想是对的。<br><br>这是YIMBY（“Yes in My Backyard”）运动面临的核心挑战，该运动是一个由学者、政策制定者和草根活动家组成的意识形态多元化的组织，致力于一个简单得令人解除武装的想法，即在美国最繁荣的城镇建造新家园将是一件非常好的事情。作为一个智力项目，YIMBYism 取得了巨大的成功，这是有充分理由的。大量证据表明，增加住房供应以满足住房需求可以 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/mac.20170388">促进经济增长</a>并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/sites/default/files/publication/103472/why-housing-matters-for-upward-mobility-evidence-and-indicators-for-practitioners-and-policymakers.pdf">刺激向上流动</a>。甚至有初步证据表明，遏制当地土地使用监管可能有助于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://corinnelow.github.io/LafortuneLow.pdf">扭转工薪阶层家庭婚姻的崩溃</a>，这可不是一件小事。在研究地方土地利用的经济学家和法律学者中，关于分区改革的争论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3917621">基本上已经结束</a>。<br><br>然而，YIMBY 运动未能克服选民根深蒂固的怀疑，他们凭直觉认为新家园意味着新邻居，而新邻居可能意味着新的麻烦。<br><br>以加利福尼亚州为例，YIMBY 立法者在那里取得了最大的进步。自 2016 年以来，加利福尼亚州立法机构通过了一系列措施，以取代当地一些最恶劣的土地使用法规，促使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/california-accessory-dwelling-units-legalization-yimby/671648/">附属住宅单元</a>蓬勃发展。但是，尽管有无可争议的证据表明住房负担能力危机仍在迫使数十万低收入和中等收入家庭离开该州，但许多加州人强烈反对最近的住房推动，以至于出现了真正的危险是选民将在 2024 年通过一项<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ourneighborhoodvoices.com/">投票措施</a>来推翻改革。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/california-single-family-zoning-housing/673758/">耶路撒冷德姆萨斯：加州并不特别</a><br><br>为了理解为什么加州选民如此难以赢得支持，陈·扎克伯格倡议（Chan Zuckerberg Initiative）是 YIMBYism 的主要慈善倡导者之一，委托开展了一系列焦点小组和调查，最终于去年发布了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://chanzuckerberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/CZI-The-California-Dream-Housing-White-Paper.pdf?_hsmi=202158258&amp;_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8dQATs5ekYbaqhSew-av8OArDJ7C4yOHPrIUsuYhkhO1dam2ool1Zxkycq6j036i1tXC4bn1DOSIMaxaVITCf_Crl2SrOS70pC7rP7s8X1jQ_TpxA">一份报告</a>。作者表示，“我们听到的大多数租客和业主都表示，他们对附近的经济适用房解决方案持谨慎态度，担心这会导致犯罪、噪音、垃圾、非法倾倒以及普遍缺乏财产维护。 ”此外，尽管绝大多数受访者“广泛接受多样性作为其社区当前或理想的特征”，但他们对邻居比他们贫穷得多的想法深感不安。<br><br>这种怀疑并不是金州独有的。今年 1 月，州长凯西·霍赫尔 (Kathy Hochul) 公布了“纽约住房契约”，这是一套雄心勃勃的改革措施，旨在提高纽约市及其臭名昭著的昂贵郊区的住房生产。到五月， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://manhattan.institute/article/nyc-housing-crisis-next-steps-after-new-york-housing-compact-fails">住房契约已经失效</a>。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/local-government-power-nimby-denver/674164/">科罗拉多州</a>、亚利桑那州和德克萨斯州的全州分区改革提案也以失败告终。<br><br>这一切并不意味着 YIMBY 主义注定要失败。但如果 YIMBY 想要推动更多美国人朝他们的方向发展，他们最好少些威吓，多些倾听。<br><br>一些最热心的 YIMBY 坚信自己的正义，采取了道德姿态，谴责顽固的房主是势利者或偏执狂，并呼吁采取全面的立法措施，剥夺地方政府的土地使用权，并进一步限制房东的能力。选择他们的租户。理查德·卡伦伯格的新书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Excluded-Zoning-NIMBYism-Class-Build/dp/1541701461"><em>排除》</em></a>是这种情感的完美升华。<br><br>卡伦伯格以其对精英大学种族偏好的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/supreme-court-harvard-affirmative-action-legacy-admissions-equity/671869/">逆向批评</a>而闻名，他将自己的公共生活奉献给了种族和经济融合的论证。排除者并不满足于对可能会吸引房主自身利益的排他性分区提出审慎的理由，<em>他们</em>认为这种做法是一种道德上的愤怒——阶级主义，也隐含着种族主义——我们需要一场道德运动来根除它。联邦政府全力出动，仿照上个世纪反对种族隔离的斗争。为此，卡伦伯格呼吁制定一项经济公平住房法案，允许对歧视穷人或对不同阶层产生不必要的不​​同影响的分区政策提出诉讼，并由法官决定什么是必要的。这实际上相当于联邦政府对单户住宅分区的禁令，也会威胁到无数其他分区政策，并且在很大程度上通过基于模糊、主观的法律标准威胁提起昂贵的诉讼来威慑地方政府。<br><br>虽然这一论点肯定会引起一些社会正义进步人士的共鸣，但不太可能说服那些担心社区变化前景的焦虑的房主和租客。加州大学戴维斯分校土地使用法教授克里斯·埃尔门多夫警告说，将分区改革视为经济正义问题可能会适得其反。今天的富裕郊区居民可能会对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/race-and-zoning">他们犯有种族敌意的说法感到不满</a>，但他们完全乐意被指控为色盲阶级偏见。<br><br>反对在自家后院修建新住房的人可能不是特别开明，但他们也不是妄想。顾名思义，排他性分区是一种通过部署地方土地使用监管来吸引富裕居民并阻止贫困居民来改善地方税基的策略。美国的地方公共服务主要由地方财产税和其他市政收入（例如销售税、停车费和污水处理费）提供资金。人们不必是一个可恨的势利小人，也能认识到，虽然一些新来者在当地创造的收入会多于他们在服务中获得的收入，但其他人却不会。<br><br>事实上，这些地方财政压力可以说是塑造美国支离破碎的大都市地理的核心力量。正如普林斯顿大学经济学家利亚·布斯坦（Leah Boustan） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://press.princeton.edu/books/hardcover/9780691150871/competition-in-the-promised-land"><em>在《应许之地的竞争》一书中</em></a>指出的那样，战后时代的“白人逃亡”在很大程度上是由这些财政问题驱动的。随着贫穷的黑人移民前往东北部、中西部和西部的城市中心，大量富裕的白人家庭搬到平均收入高于他们离开的城市的郊区管辖区。毫无疑问，这种向外移民的部分原因是白人不愿与黑人邻居一起生活，但由于这一时期美国城市的隔离程度如此之高，大部分逃亡者都来自纯白人社区。城市居民离开这些白人社区的动机不是担心与黑人邻居进行社会交往，而是担心与有不同需求和优先事项的低收入邻居进行财政交往。 “搬到郊区，”布斯坦写道，“让白人家庭能够将自己与中心城市提供的不断变化的当地公共产品和财政义务隔离开来。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2015/07/white-flight-alive-and-well/399980/">阅读：白色飞行从未结束</a><br><br>鉴于这些强大的财政激励措施，小型郊区司法管辖区的邻避主义几乎是不可避免的。与其指望道德劝说能够改变这些社区的分区政策，YIMBY 人最好采取一种更加谦虚和现实的方法，努力与郊区的邻避者相向而行。<br><br>赢得郊区房主的青睐的一个直接方法是推进住房改革，帮助他们积累财富，正如埃尔门多夫<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.city-journal.org/article/the-housing-treadmill">所建议的</a>那样。例如，附属住宅单元的合法化可以让普通房主富裕起来，无论公平与否，普通房主都比大型开发商享有更多的公众同情，并且可以动员他们反对成本增加的市政影响费和自由裁量审查程序。作为额外的好处，这种改革让 YIMBY 能够在尊重财产权和个人自由的基础上发出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.city-journal.org/article/where-are-all-the-republican-yimbys">更加乐观的呼吁</a>，这一主张帮助俄勒冈州、犹他州和蒙大拿州通过了分区改革法律。<br><br>当面对坚决的郊区阻力时，例如在纽约州南部，霍赫尔的住房契约被证明是一个巨大的政治负担，YIMBYs 应该集中精力放松大城市的土地使用监管。在人口较多的司法管辖区，对住房建设的反对往往不那么强烈，部分原因是这些地区的贫富居民比例从定义上来说更难改变。城市社区也比郊区社区更具活力：其中租房者、年轻人、低收入家庭和其他住房流失率高于平均水平的人口比例过高。社区变化是这些社区生活的一个事实。如果城市核心区的分区改革取得成功，那么较小社区的住房增长将更加引人注目。<br><br>冒着激怒反商业进步人士的风险，YIMBY 还应该采取更多措施<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/full/10.1146/annurev-polisci-051921-102505">培养大型雇主作为政治盟友</a>。较低的住房成本是吸引和留住工人的有力工具，大型雇主可以对州立法机构施加重大影响。加州科技行业的雇主在反对严格分区的斗争中发挥了重要作用并非巧合——他们敏锐地意识到，随着金州住房成本的上涨，他们要么支付更高的工资，要么眼睁睁地看着他们的工人逃往城市在爱达荷州或内华达州。<br><br>最后，YIMBY 应该努力软化最初推动排斥性分区的地方财政激励措施。耶鲁大学法学院的扎卡里·利斯考 (Zachary Liscow) 发现， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nyulawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/NYULawReview-92-6-Liscow.pdf">当各州承担更大比例的学校经费时</a>，富人会变得更愿意搬到较贫穷的司法管辖区，可能是因为这样做将不再让他们承担为大量学生提供支持服务的特殊负担。纳税很少的邻居。与这种模式一致，他发现集中的学校经费导致低收入城市的税收降低。<br><br>类似的逻辑也适用于国家对治安和公共安全工作的资助。如果邻避者担心低收入移民的涌入会导致犯罪和骚乱激增，正如陈·扎克伯格研究所的调查结果强烈表明的那样，那么增加国家对当地执法机构的援助可能会减轻他们的担忧。一些主要的社交媒体左派人士不以为然地将这种支持分区改革和“破窗”监管的结合称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://darrellowens.substack.com/p/whos-who-the-dictionary-of-in-my">监狱城市化</a>”，但社交媒体左派当然不是目标受众。<br><br>诚然，改变地方财政激励措施将是一项重大任务，这将遭到选民的抵制，他们担心在新的财政分配下会失败。但地方政府收入的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/policy-centers/cross-center-initiatives/state-and-local-finance-initiative/state-and-local-backgrounders/state-and-local-revenues#local">30%</a>已经以州政府转移支付的形式出现。增加州政府为地方警务或公共教育提供资金的责任将是一个相对温和且可能非常受欢迎的变化，特别是与强制生产受契约限制的经济适用住房和其他优先事项的公平份额要求相比。 YIMBY 离开了。<br><br>修改地方财政激励措施、与地区商业精英结成联盟、帮助一些拥有丰富房产的房主变得更富有，不会带来一个从东海岸到西海岸的综合社区的平等新千年，但它将帮助 YIMBY 建立一个更有说服力的案例住房增长符合郊区居民开明的自身利益，否则他们可能会担心税收负担上升和房价下跌。这不是一个糟糕的开始。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/yimby-california-social-justice-kahlenberg/674714/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/yimby-california-social-justice-kahlenberg/674714/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Has a New Gulag]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>莫斯科恢复了苏联时代的劳改营。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/H1TZce-E-6m-ZKob-s31lEruE4c=/0x0:8867x4988/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/AP23192663533575/original.jpg" alt="乌克兰伊齐乌姆的一间牢房" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>叶夫根尼·马洛莱特卡/美联社</figcaption></figure>1978年，博赫丹·克林查克离开苏联，前往伊朗寻求政治庇护。克林恰克是乌克兰人，出生在利沃夫附近。 1949 年，在他的兄弟作为“乌克兰民族主义者”被捕后，他的家人被驱逐到俄罗斯远东地区的哈巴罗夫斯克。 1957年，克林恰克本人因“反苏煽动”被捕；即使在被释放后，他仍然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://museum.khpg.org/1142682865">受到持续的监视</a>。在越过边境逃亡并被伊朗人送回后，克林恰克最终被关进了一个名为 Perm-36 的集中营，这是苏联最后的大型政治监狱之一。作为最后一批苏联政治犯之一，他一直呆在那里直到 1990 年。<br><br>克林查克获释后的三十年里，发生了很多事情。 Perm-36 成为一座蓬勃发展的博物馆和纪念场所，每年接待数以万计的游客，其中包括成群结队的学童。 2014年，又被关闭。俄罗斯前囚犯和历史学家出版了古拉格回忆录和历史，举办了会议，举办了展览，制作了纪录片。然后，在过去的几年里， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/putins-plot-against-russias-future/620930/">他们的组织被取缔</a>，他们的领导人被流放或忽视。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ukraine-russia-war-consequences/673792/">阅读：战争及其后果</a><br><br>如今，同一古拉格系统的新版本正在重建，特别是对于乌克兰人。记者、战争罪调查人员和清算项目等专门团体<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/russia-ukraine-war-potemkin-occupation-murder-torture/672841/">已经记录了</a>俄罗斯占领下的乌克兰领土上发生的逮捕、谋杀、监狱和酷刑室事件。慢慢地，人们越来越清楚，这些不仅仅是针对乌克兰抵抗的临时反应。它们是长期计划的一部分：建造一个庞大的营地和惩罚殖民地系统——一个新的古拉格。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/ukraine-russia-prisons-civilians-torture-detainees-88b4abf2efbf383272eed9378be13c72">美联社</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/ukraine-russia-prisons-civilians-torture-detainees-88b4abf2efbf383272eed9378be13c72">昨天</a>报道称，有证据表明俄罗斯和白俄罗斯至少有 40 个战俘营，以及被占领的乌克兰有 63 个正式和非正式监狱，关押着大约 10,000 名乌克兰人。其中一些是战俘：俄罗斯监狱监测组织 Gulagu.net<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://gulagu.net/cases/voyna-v-ukraine">有证据表明</a>，俄罗斯监狱中的乌克兰士兵没有适当的证件或战俘身份。但大多数乌克兰囚犯是在被占领土被捕或绑架的平民。<br><br>正如古拉格在鼎盛时期一样，奴隶劳动是这些集中营的目的之一。一些被囚禁的乌克兰人被迫为俄罗斯士兵挖战壕、修建防御工事，并挖掘乱葬坑。古拉格的设计目的还在于向更广泛的人群灌输恐惧，新的集中营系统也是如此。平民会因为一些轻微的罪行而被监禁和遭受酷刑——美联社援引了在自行车上系一条乌克兰颜色的丝带为例——或者有时根本没有任何理由。 “清算项目”收集了许多俄罗斯士兵变得偏执并审问普通人（其中许多人是民间组织的志愿者）的例子，询问他们与乌克兰安全部门、中央情报局甚至乔治·索罗斯的开放社会基金会的联系。美联社描述了一名来自乌克兰扎波罗热地区的平民俘虏，她被从牢房中拉出来，开车绕城一周，并被告知要识别亲乌克兰的人。 1937-38 年大清洗时期，苏联秘密警察同样偏执、同样恐惧，不仅对普通民众，而且对彼此也同样如此。最近的内讧表明，俄罗斯军队在被占领的乌克兰也可能达到这一阶段。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/counteroffensive-ukraine-zelensky-crimea/673781/">摘自2023年6月号：反攻</a><br><br>与苏联古拉格集中营一样，新的俄罗斯营地网络也不是暂时的，除非乌克兰人能够收回自己的领土，否则它将会扩大。美联社获得了今年 1 月的一份俄罗斯文件，其中描述了到 2026 年在被占领的乌克兰领土上建造 25 个新监狱和 6 个拘留中心的计划。与苏联古拉格一样，这个系统混乱且无法无天。人们未经审判就被定罪。他们的文件已丢失。有时他们会无缘无故地被保留，或者无缘无故地被释放。他们的亲属没有收到有关他们的任何信息，也无法找到或联系他们。最终，他们也可能被迫上前线。这无疑是俄罗斯囚犯的命运，他们中的许多人现在被要求签署动员文件，如果拒绝，就会遭到殴打和酷刑。与过去一样，俄罗斯监狱长似乎<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.svoboda.org/a/32502251.html">已经获得了配额</a>，即他们需要提供的囚犯数量，以实现某些中央计划。<br><br>历史的回响不可能是偶然的。克格勃曾经教导新员工学习该机构的历史，俄罗斯安全部门显然也在做同样的事情：他们正在执行在苏联时期“有效”的镇压政策，将博赫丹·克林恰克和他的兄弟等人关进监狱。但这段历史也解释了乌克兰的反应。任何想知道为什么乌克兰人继续战斗，为什么他们不断要求更多武器，为什么他们对缓慢的跨大西洋外交感到沮丧，为什么他们看起来愤怒或“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-zelensky-nato-membership-complaint-is-unreasonable">不合理</a>”的人都应该记住这一点：古拉格应该属于过去。现在它属于现在。如果乌克兰人不希望它成为他们未来的一部分，他们将不得不将这些难民营以及管理这些难民营的人从乌克兰土地上撤走。在他们成功之前，任何帮助都是不够的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 16:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/ Russia-gulag-ukraine/674705/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/ Russia-gulag-ukraine/674705/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[And Just Like That Addresses Its Che Diaz Problem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在第二季进行到一半的时候，《<em>欲望都市》</em>的重启给这个最令人讨厌的角色带来了意想不到的深度。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/SBHCRiaUlqCALC2hYkKUaZ8KzJc=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/AJLT/original.jpg" alt="切·迪亚兹和米兰达·霍布斯在《就这样》" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>克雷格·布兰肯霍恩 / 马克斯</figcaption></figure>本故事包含<strong>《就这样》</strong>第二季<em><strong>第五集的剧透</strong></em><em><strong>。</strong></em><br><br>没有人穿着哈佛连帽衫看起来像辛西娅·尼克松饰演的严肃律师米兰达·霍布斯在<em>《欲望都市》</em>第一季的一集中那样不舒服。在“已婚猪湾”中，米兰达同意在她公司的年度垒球比赛中相亲。但当一位同事向米兰达介绍她的对象时，她意识到她的同事们错误地判断了她没有男朋友的原因。米兰达在见到一位名叫西德（乔安娜·阿德勒饰）的完美女人后感到尴尬，她责备她的同事对她的性取向的假设。 “是的，我不是同性恋，”她说。 “天啊，什么时候单身变成了同性恋？”<br><br> 1998 年播出的《已婚猪湾》聚焦于已婚人士与单身人士之间的“冷战”——在一场酝酿已久的冲突中，夫妻们将单身女性视为敌人或怜悯的对象。在米兰达的案例中，她所在公司的合伙人对她作为有伴侣的女同性恋的尊重远远超过作为单身异性恋女性的尊重，这促使她与西德建立虚假的关系。米兰达的老板邀请这对夫妇共进晚餐后，米兰达坦白了这场猜谜游戏，但在电梯下楼时亲吻了西德。 “是的，绝对是直的，”她宣称，西德很快就证实了这一结论。<br><br>自该集播出以来的 25 年里，它已经成为<em>《欲望都市</em>》偶尔会嫉妒的酷儿粉丝的最爱，哪怕只是因为它巨大的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://z-p3.www.instagram.com/p/Cs9Gjxru6PT/">模因潜力</a>。它的部分魅力来自于尼克松现实生活中的浪漫轨迹：这位演员于 2003 年与她的长期男性伴侣分手，并在原剧结束时开始与教育活动家克里斯汀·马里诺尼 (Christine Marinoni) 约会。从那时起，她公开承认自己<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2012/01/30/cynthia-nixon-being-bisexual-not-choice#toggle-gdpr">是双性恋</a>，与马里诺尼结婚，并选择公开承认<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/shes-here-shes-queer-and-cynthia-nixon-wants-you-to-get-used-to-it">自己是酷儿</a>。甚至<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.them.us/story/sex-and-the-city-reboot-miranda-bisexual">在 2021 年</a><em>《欲望都市》</em>重启的消息得到证实之前，许多酷儿粉丝就希望该剧能够重新审视米兰达垒球比赛中首次提出的可能性。在某些圈子里，米兰达是这部剧中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lofficielusa.com/pop-culture/sex-and-the-city-book-miranda-hobbes">最有抱负的人物</a>——是这群人中最冷静的一个，也是最有可能警告她的朋友们把一生都围绕着男人的人。长期以来，她一直在一个节目中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2022/tv/news/cynthia-nixon-miranda-sex-and-the-city-queer-lesbian-1235281614/">充当酷儿女性的不完美化身</a>，该节目<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2021/01/when-sex-and-the-city-returns-will-it-finally-get-queer-people-right">对酷儿的处理</a>有时会转向<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/missmollymary/status/1678835592325660672">滑稽的</a>冒犯领域。<br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2021/12/and-just-like-that-review-sex-and-city/620959/"><em>《就这样》</em>的第一季</a>中，这部新剧讲述了<em>《欲望都市》中</em>三位原版人物的故事，现年 50 多岁的米兰达确实得到了她的酷儿故事主线。但对于许多粉丝来说，这段经历是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://medium.com/@allegrahirschman/miranda-was-always-already-queer-5708e198aee0">苦乐参半的</a>——很大程度上是因为爱情兴趣开启了她的觉醒。米兰达仍然与史蒂夫（大卫·艾根伯格饰）保持着婚姻关系，她深深地爱上了非二元的单口喜剧演员切·迪亚兹（萨拉·拉米雷斯饰），切·迪亚兹是一位多角恋、泛性恋的混乱代理人，她共同主持了一个播客<em>《X、Y和我》。</em>描述为涵盖“性别角色、性角色和肉桂卷”。一位<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tiktok.com/@cbc/video/7253475865772707078">受压抑</a>、成就斐然的律师中年酷儿觉醒的想法一点也不不可思议——她可能会迷恋一位年轻的、吸大麻的煽动者。尽管如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-pop-culture/agony-ecstasy-mirandas-coming-sex-city-reboot-rcna13213">切还是很恼火</a>。在他们的第一个场景中，切通过称嘉莉（莎拉·杰西卡·帕克饰）为“卡莉女士”来欢迎他们的两位顺性别共同主持人加入播客。 Cis”介绍自己为“酷儿、非二元性别、墨西哥爱尔兰天后，代表这两种无聊性别之外的所有人”，然后按下音板上的一个按钮，用响亮的“醒来的时刻！”来打断这首歌。<br><br>在萨姆·桑德斯 (Sam Sanders) 的播客<em>《Into It》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://open.spotify.com/episode/3NSBFcZpl5vZRrT5gsqFX7?si=d6159ba252cb47c5&amp;nd=1">最近一集中</a>，该节目的编剧之一萨曼莎·厄比 (Samantha Irby) 将迪亚兹比作“那种将一杯咖啡变成殖民主义教训的人……切就像变成了 12 的那个人。” ”自从珍妮·谢克特（Jenny Schecter）这个令人难以忍受的天真无邪的<em>《拉字至上》</em>中心人物以来，还没有一个虚构的角色让我认识的几乎所有酷儿以及无数陌生人如此彻底地烦恼，他们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.buzzfeed.com/lyapalater/hey-its-che-diaz-jokes">推文</a>、Instagram 帖子和 TikTok 都出现在我的屏幕上。引用<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/obsessed/and-just-like-thats-che-diaz-is-the-worst-character-on-tv"><em>《每日野兽报》</em></a>一篇特别热情的评论：“这样的角色如此令人发指，真是不幸。没有人<em>愿意</em>将系列中唯一的新 LGBTQ+ 角色挑为最差的。然而切·迪亚兹让我们别无选择。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/06/and-just-like-that-season-2-review/674474/">阅读：曾经定义时代的演出的幽灵</a><br><br>然后，我惊讶地发现自己在最新一集中对切产生<em>了类似同情的</em>感觉。第一季结束时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2022/02/and-just-like-finale-miranda-che/621487/">米兰达一反常态地离开了</a>史蒂夫、她的朋友们，以及一个重要的职业机会，跟随切去了洛杉矶，这位喜剧演员希望在那里为他们的半自传式成长情景喜剧的试播集开绿灯。 。切在第一季中很容易成为模仿的对象，而第二季则清楚地表明， <em>《就这样》</em>编剧室并不是漫无目的地从网络社会正义术语中拉出来的。从周四播出的第五集开始，该剧增加了切的深度——这是一个值得欢迎的转变，也为米兰达创造了更多的空间来解决她在想象未来成为切的住家拉拉队长时所面临的一些存在主义问题。<br><br>在由 Irby 和 Lucas Froehlich 共同编剧的这一集中，Che 观看了纽约焦点小组对他们的节目<em>《Che Pasa》</em>试播集的试映反馈。该团体中的一名年轻有色人种酷儿成员对以切为原型的角色提出了质疑，称他们的故事情节是“虚假的、经过净化的、表演性的、俗气的、老爸笑话、非二元体验的狗屎版本。 ” （“这很糟糕，”他们补充道。）这些批评立即让切落泪，粉碎了他们对定义人生的工作意义的信念。当米兰达后来试图安慰他们说受访者不知道他们在说什么时，切拒绝了她：“一个来自布鲁克林的性别酷儿把它搞砸了！电话是从屋内传来的。”<br><br>切本可以直接回应现实生活中观众对他们的抱怨，但这种交流之所以有效，是因为它让我们看到了从漫画中出现真实<em>角色</em>的潜力。任何类型的艺术创作都是一个极其脆弱的过程，当作品是自传体时更是如此。对于酷儿和跨性别者，尤其是有色人种来说，在好莱坞取得重大突破往往意味着要应对该行业令人筋疲力尽的结构性障碍和对容易消除的刻板印象的偏好。这种类型的反馈可能会令人士气低落，但这是预料之中的。然而，社区内部的判断力受到的打击要大得多，这使得切受到的批评尤其具有毁灭性。 “我花了 46 年才弄清楚我是谁，”切告诉米兰达，“然后一个焦点小组花了一个小时就毁了我。”<br><br>到目前为止，让切如此令人抓狂的部分原因在于，这部剧本身似乎不确定自己的角色是谁，以及她们在三位核心女性的故事中扮演什么角色。在第一季中，切是嘉莉的年轻陪衬，嘉莉在播客中扮演切的正经异性恋对手，因为她对关于酷儿的数字笑话和有关性的问题感到不舒服。夏洛特（克里斯汀·戴维斯饰）并没有真正与切互动，只是质疑为什么米兰达<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-pop-culture/agony-ecstasy-mirandas-coming-sex-city-reboot-rcna13213">几乎在一夜之间</a>就毁掉了她与史蒂夫的关系。切的存在，似乎不仅仅是为了向米兰达表明她在婚姻中并不幸福，也是为了让三人了解他们的特权——作为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/24/arts/television/sex-and-the-city-girls-girlfriends-run-the-world.html">对原版<em>《欲望都市》</em>的纠正，</a>同时扩展新系列所描绘的生活类型。 。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2022/02/and-just-like-finale-miranda-che/621487/">阅读：我们需要谈谈米兰达</a><br><br>对于一个角色来说，需要付出很多努力。非二元人物确实存在于其他节目中，故事情节<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2021/11/18/1056817713/sort-of-hbo-max-review">丰富而复杂</a>，但在<em>《欲望都市》</em>的阴影下，像切这样的角色总是很难被认为是该剧最接近非二元人物的角色。像。在最初的竞选中，嘉莉曾将双性恋称为“前往同性恋镇途中的中途停留”。因此，不难理解为什么在重启时加入一个被认为是“机会均等的混淆者”的角色会被视为一种尝试，正如詹姆斯·法特拉（James Factora）在《二元论》中所写的那样，试图“给……那些在二元体系之外的 Z 世代” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.them.us/story/and-just-like-that-mediocre-nonbinary-representation">写下</a>猫薄荷。 2021年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.them.us/story/and-just-like-that-mediocre-nonbinary-representation"><em>他们</em></a>。<br><br>让 X 一代思考他们的故事在年轻酷儿人群中的局限性，这给了<em>《就这样》的</em>观众第一个真正的信号，表明该剧并不认为这位喜剧演员实际上<em>代表</em>了他们的整个社区。在<em>《Into It》节目</em>中，厄比表示切的高调性格是“故意的”。然而，在第二季中，“切的诡计开始崩溃。”我们在艾比和弗罗利希的剧集中清楚地看到了这一点，但它也在接下来的两集中继续存在。在不剧透任何内容的情况下，切对意义的探索让他们更接近嘉莉，并促使米兰达以深度和好奇心而不是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.salon.com/2023/07/09/and-just-like-that-miranda-che/">尴尬、自私的冲动</a>来探索她的酷儿。<br><br>到了本季第七集， <em>《就这样》</em>更接近满足粉丝们对这位新的典型酷儿米兰达的希望，尽管它并没有让她与那个不愿亲吻席德的米兰达和解。史蒂夫有更多的空间来表达自己对米兰达旅程的复杂反应，以及对他们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thecut.com/2022/01/sex-and-the-citys-steve-deserves-better.html">深爱的</a>、尽管<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://graziamagazine.com/us/articles/reconsidering-miranda-steve-sex-and-the-city/">有时不稳定的</a>婚姻的解体的复杂反应。令人惊讶的是，切在剧团中塑造的角色比房地产恶棍西玛（萨里塔·乔杜里饰）或米兰达研究生院教授兼室友尼亚（凯伦·皮特曼饰）更加充实。谢天谢地，因为我不确定自己能否再承受一次“醒来的时刻！”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 14:37:49 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/and-just-like-that-c​​he-diaz-character/674703/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/and-just-like-that-c​​he-diaz-character/674703/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Is a Glass of Wine Harmless? Wrong Question.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>最新的饮酒建议忽视了快乐的价值。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/LhxMO4yoXcC8qZw70hecla-jF4E=/1x0:2444x1374/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_56464858_copy/original.jpg" alt="一个人检查一杯酒的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>图像/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br>不久前，酒精对你有好处。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blog.iwfs.org/2014/08/french-paradox-how-a-60-minutes-segment-transformed-red-wine-consumption-in-america/">1991 年的<i>《60 分钟》</i>节目</a>中，一位法国研究人员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njm1LkXP2sg">声称</a>，饮用红酒对法国人的健康有益。事实证明，这一论点受到葡萄酒消费群体的欢迎，并促使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/014067369190542W">学术论文</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/310/6988/1165.short">提出</a>红酒消费与心血管疾病之间存在反比关系。科学家甚至提出了一种解释红酒健康的机制理论，其中涉及一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://europepmc.org/article/med/7499059">名为白藜芦醇的</a>化合物。<br><br>其他人很快就对红酒与长寿是否真的存在因果关系的可能性表示怀疑。 “酒精对你有好处”的说法被侵蚀了，在过去的一年里，似乎已经完全崩溃了。许多研究人员现在认为，基本上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/5376552/how-much-alcohol-to-drink-study/"><i>任何</i>数量</a>的酒精都对你有害。 <i>《纽约时报》</i>一月份的一篇文章标题为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/13/well/mind/alcohol-health-effects.html">即使是一点点酒精也会损害你的健康</a>”。因此<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ccsa.ca/canadas-guidance-alcohol-and-health">，包括加拿大政府在内的</a>一些人建议，最安全的选择就是<i>根本</i>不喝酒。<br><br>过量饮酒显然会导致严重的身体和情感问题。这没有争议。然而：<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DkS1pkKpILY">最近的</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/wellness/2023/03/31/moderate-drinking-alcohol-wine-risks/">言论</a>转向禁欲，远远超出了避免大量饮酒的合理建议，并且忽视了快乐的价值。<br><br><a href="http://v/">阅读：每天喝酒几乎肯定不会伤害你</a><br><br>即使在酒精领域之外，一种与快乐无关的健康建议方法现在也很流行，并且正在渗透到公众中，有时会产生荒谬的结果。最近，一位读者问我：<i>有没有关于性高潮对健康有益的数据？</i>我不知道来自随机实验的可靠数据表明，拥有更多的性高潮可以改善健康。无论如何，这不是高潮的意义。高潮的要点在于它们很有趣。我们不需要证明健康益处就可以拥有它们。<br><br>公共卫生建议有时基于“字典式”标准——将对健康的影响放在第一位、第二位和第三位，而忽略其他考虑因素，包括享受。例如，适用于肉类消费的词典标准表明，我们必须始终吃熟透的汉堡，因为这是避免<i>大肠杆菌</i>风险的最佳方法，尽管熟透的汉堡无味。更一般地说，一些公共卫生领域的人避免讨论专制主义带来的意想不到的负面后果。在冠状病毒大流行期间，一些官员强烈主张长期关闭学校，认为让孩子们待在家里是防止学生和教师在学校传播病毒的唯一方法。从技术意义上来说，这是正确的，但这项建议没有考虑到这些关闭给儿童带来的巨大成本，而这些成本应该与任何好处进行权衡。<br><br>回到酒精问题上，如果现有的最佳证据表明，即使是适度饮酒也会造成<i>巨大</i>危害，那么快乐不可知论可能是有道理的。它不是。我还应该强调，这些数据从根本上来说是有缺陷的，因为我们拥有的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-28735-5">最大</a>、最常被引用的研究是观察性的，而不是随机的。而且适量饮酒的人与不适量饮酒的人的特征是不同的。<br><br> In 2018, <i>The Lancet</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thelancet.com/article/S0140-6736(18)31310-2/fulltext">published a comprehensive study</a> on the link between alcohol consumption and cancer, heart disease, and other illnesses. It is an extraordinary work of scholarship, combining hundreds of previous papers. And the results indicate an upward trend in cancer, in particular, as alcohol consumption increases. But the effects at moderate levels of drinking—say, one to two drinks a day— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/08/there-is-a-safe-level-of-alcohol/568531/">are very small</a> . For heart disease, we see the familiar <i>decrease</i> in risk at moderate drinking levels, and an increase with higher amounts.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/america-drinking-alone-problem/619017/">From the July/August 2021 issue: America has a drinking problem</a><br><br> <i>None of these results are convincingly causal</i> .<i> </i>It seems very likely that all associations—positive and negative—are overstated relative to the truth. Generally, when researchers are able to adjust for some demographic differences, the relationship between alcohol and health gets smaller. This, in turns, suggests that if they could <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07350015.2016.1227711">adjust for more differences</a> , it would get smaller still. Whether these relationships would be smaller but still positive, or really zero, is something we cannot know from the data we have.<br><br> We cannot conclusively prove that moderate alcohol consumption is totally benign, much less beneficial. Based on the data we have, it also seems extremely unlikely that moderate alcohol consumption is fully “bad” for your health.<br><br> If you do not enjoy, or actively dislike, alcohol, then the abstinence standard might be the right one for you. But many people do enjoy a drink from time to time: a beer with friends, a cold glass of rosé in the summer, a hot toddy in front of the fire, even just a glass of white wine while cooking at the end of a long day. If we accept that pleasure has value, and that the data are muddy, then the moderation standard makes more sense.<br><br> The pendulum on alcohol has swung too far from the 1990s. Alcohol is probably not the key to longevity. But it&#39;s not arsenic, either. In the immortal words of Cookie Monster, it&#39;s a sometime food.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/moderate-drinking-heart-disesase-cancer/674692/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/moderate-drinking-heart-disesase-cancer/674692/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Learn a Foreign Language Before It’s Too Late]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> AI translators may seem wondrous but they also erode a major part of what it is to be human. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/5M15ZusU0gok3jCRmFL6TZo4VZE=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/languages_illo_horiz/original.jpg" alt="An image of the word &quot;hello: translated into Spanish, French, and Italian, which have been obscured with the word &quot;hello&quot; written in English." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ben Kothe / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> To me, AI&#39;s scariest aspect is the so-called singularity—the threat of a runaway intelligence explosion leaving humanity in the dust. But today&#39;s state of the art in artificial intelligence is already auguring smaller but still shattering scenarios.<br><br> Some people so deeply yearn to climb Mount Everest that they prepare for years, spend vast sums of money, exhaust themselves for weeks in the climb itself, and repeatedly put their lives at risk. Does that sound like you? Or would you rather just land on its summit in a helicopter and feast yourself on the great view? And what about scaling the <em>metaphorical</em> Everest of a foreign language? Two small episodes in my life in the past month led me to serious musings along these lines.<br><br> Two weeks ago, I watched, for the first time ever, a video of myself back in 2018 in Hangzhou, China, as I struggled mightily for three minutes to make a few off-the-cuff remarks to about 20 young people from Shanghai who belonged to a club of AI enthusiasts. They had traveled 200 miles to Hangzhou to meet me for dinner, and for two and a half hours we had spoken only English together, but toward the evening&#39;s end they asked me if I wouldn&#39;t mind saying something very brief <em>in Chinese</em> for those club members who hadn&#39;t been able to make the trip. Uh-oh! Panic city! Even though I had devoted many arduous years to the study of Chinese (always thinking of the daunting phrase “Learning Chinese is a five-year lesson in humility” as a ridiculous understatement), and had worked like the devil during the previous three months in Hangzhou, I was caught way off guard by their request and, although in the end I obliged them, I felt super jittery while doing so. Shortly thereafter they sent me the video, but for all these years I hadn&#39;t dared to look at even the opening few seconds of it, so scared was I of seeing myself linguistically stumble all over the place.<br><br> But what I saw, when I finally dared to watch myself very recently, was surprising. I saw a person who was not just struggling hard to express himself in a very difficult alien tongue, but who was actually doing a fairly decent job of it, while at the same time coming across as insecure and vulnerable, yet courageously willing to take the bull by the horns. In short, today&#39;s me felt proud of my 2018 self! Since that day five years ago, sadly, my once-okay Chinese has gone to the dogs, and today I couldn&#39;t give a three-minute talk in Chinese to save my life, so I&#39;m thrilled to have proof that at one time in my life, I was actually able to wing it, actually able to give a tiny “talk” in Chinese, even if only a three-minute one.<br><br> So that&#39;s the first episode; here&#39;s the other. A few weeks ago, my very dear Italian friend Benedetto Scimemi passed away, and I spent hours writing heartfelt emails of condolence to all the members of his family. It happens that I lived in Italy for nearly three years and, on top of that, my two children and I have spoken Italian for 30 years as our family language, so my Italian is very fluent and comfortable—but, even so, it is not the Italian of a native speaker. In writing those difficult and emotional emails, I was constantly adjusting my words and phrases, lovingly remembering Benedetto and all the wonderful things we had done together, and pushing my Italian to its very limits. It took me perhaps two or three times as long as it would have taken me in English, but I did it with all my heart. I looked up lots of words in the big, heavy dictionary that I always keep right by my computer, and I felt my words were really <em>me</em> ; my caring concentration on each and every turn of phrase made them mirror my feelings of love for my late friend in the most intensely personal way. Once again I was proud of myself and of the manner in which, over decades, I had come to be able to express myself clearly, strongly, and with a deeply felt voice in a tongue that was not my mother tongue.<br><br> Over the course of my life, I have studied lots of languages to various degrees, and I jokingly call myself “pilingual,” meaning that if you were to add up the fractional levels of mastery of all the languages I&#39;ve tackled, you&#39;d get a number a bit over three, counting English as one, French as 0.8, Italian as 0.7, and going down from there, with Chinese as maybe 0.3, at its apex (probably just 0.1 today).<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/generative-ai-human-culture-philosophy/674165/">Read: The coming human renaissance</a><br><br> Leaving aside my native tongue, I have devoted many thousands of hours of my life to seven languages (French, Italian, German, Swedish, Russian, Polish, and Chinese)—sometimes flailing desperately and sometimes finding enormous gratification. But through thick and thin, I have relentlessly bashed my head against each of those languages for years, because I love each one&#39;s sounds, words, intonation patterns, idioms, proverbs, poetry, songs, and so on. It&#39;s hard to think of anything else, in the world of the mind, that has pulled me as intensely as my craving to internalize the magic logic of an alien tongue from a faraway place.<br><br> But today we have Google Translate. Today we have DeepL. Today we have ChatGPT—and so on. There&#39;s no need for me to list all the powerful technologies that allow anyone today—a monolingual American, say, who has never devoted a single moment to learning, say, Chinese—to write fluent passages in Chinese. Today it&#39;s a piece of cake to send an email in a tongue you don&#39;t know a word of. You just click on “Translate” and presto! There it is! Or at least, there it is, in a certain sense. Assuming that there are no egregious translational blunders (which there often still are), what you are sending off is slick but soulless text.<br><br> Just imagine if the Shanghai AI club had asked me to say a few words for the club&#39;s absent members not in Chinese but in English, and then, while I was speaking, they ran my English words through a speech-transcribing app, then a translation app, then a speech-producing app, so that my English words came out <em>, in real time,</em> in Chinese. (In fact, if this were happening today, the speech-producing app could even use my very own voice, speaking with a perfect Mandarin accent!) Had the club gone that techie-type route, which they might well have liked to do, we could have bypassed any need for me to struggle and strain to express myself in their tongue. For both me and the club members, it would have been effortless.<br><br> However, in this scenario, the video watchers would be deprived of coming to know key aspects of the very human personality of their invitee. They would not see Douglas Hofstadter (known in Chinese as “Hou Daoren”) groping for Chinese words, would not witness his insecurity, his vulnerability, or, for that matter, his dogged determination; they would merely see an American casually speaking in his native tongue (though what they would <em>hear</em> is perfect Chinese); they would get no sense for the <em>real</em> me, who had devoted thousands of hours, spread out over many years, to grappling with their native tongue. My <em>ideas</em> would come across, more or less, but not those hidden aspects of my <em>self</em> .<br><br> But let me play devil&#39;s advocate for a moment. Today&#39;s AI technology allows people of different cultures to communicate instantly and effortlessly with one another. Wow! Isn&#39;t that a centuries-long dream come true, weaving the world ever more tightly together? Isn&#39;t it a wonderful miracle? Isn&#39;t the soon-to-arrive world where everyone can effortlessly speak every language just glorious?<br><br> Some readers will certainly say “yes,” but I would say “no.” In fact, I see this looming scenario as a great tragedy. I see it as the beginning of the end of the age-old tradition of learning foreign languages—not only here in America, but even in lands like Holland and Sweden, fabled for their citizens&#39; near-universal mastery of several tongues. The problem is that people of all cultures instinctively follow the path of least resistance.<br><br> Why would anyone want to devote thousands of hours to learning a foreign language if, by contrast, they could simply talk into their cellphone and it would instantly spit out “the same message” in any language of their choice, in their own voice, and with a perfect accent to boot? Who wouldn&#39;t want to be able to have complex conversations with anyone they wish, in any country, no matter what language it involves? Why bother to take countless courses in Chinese and still feel deeply inadequate in it when, in a flash, you can communicate not only in Chinese but also in French, Hungarian, Swahili, and so on?<br><br> Suppose I had composed my condolences to Benedetto&#39;s family in English and had then run them through a translation program such as DeepL. The words would have come out very differently from what I wrote in Italian. When I was <em>writing</em> in Italian, I was <em>thinking</em> in Italian, not in English. I was using words and phrases that I have made my own over decades, by having countless intimate conversations with close Italian friends (such as Benedetto himself), by reading hundreds of children&#39;s books in Italian to my kids when they were little tykes, by listening hundreds of times to CDs of lilting Italian songs from the 1930s, by devouring Italian newspapers, by giving untold dozens of lectures in Italian, by watching scores of old Italian movies, by memorizing a few Italian poems, and so on. All that unique flavor, reflecting the myriad idiosyncratic pathways by which I lovingly internalized the Italian language, would be missing from an email that I composed in English and that was instantly converted into Italian by a machine.<br><br> You might say that such a loss is a small price to pay—a <em>teeny</em> price to pay!—for the amazing luxury of being able to produce flawless, flowing emails in a hundred different languages, the luxury of being able to give lectures in real time in a hundred different languages, and so forth and so on. Well, I would reply that the “you” who is “writing” or “speaking” so fluently in all these different languages is not <em>you</em> at all. It is, rather, a deepfake version (or a set of deepfake versions) of you.<br><br> When I was in the roughest times in my endless battles with the Chinese language, I often wished that I could just get an injection that would make me perfectly fluent in Chinese in a flash. How wonderful it would be to be able, at last, to understand everyone around me, to say anything I wanted to say, and so on! But when I thought about it for only a few seconds, I realized that after getting such an injection, I would not feel <em>proud</em> of having learned Chinese by struggling for many years. My instant fluency in Chinese would, in that case, be a trivial acquisition rather than a precious goal obtained thanks to immense hard work. It would mean nothing to me, emotionally. It would be like arriving at the summit of Everest in a helicopter. It would be like taking a new wonder drug that hugely boosted my muscles and hugely sped up my reflexes, making me (even at age 78!) suddenly able to run faster than anyone else in the world. Next thing you know, this old geezer would be winning a gold medal in the Olympic 400 meters. But big deal! “My” gold medal would be a hollow victory proving nothing about my athletic abilities. It would be purely the result of technological cheating. Likewise, my Chinese-fluency injection would be a hollow victory, because “my” Chinese would not in any way represent my very human, very fallible, but also very determined mind and spirit.<br><br> When, in my teenage years, I was striving so passionately to learn French, I sometimes wished that I had just grown up in France with my American parents, so that both French and English were 100 percent native to me. But when I thought about it more carefully, I realized that the reason I was so in love with French was precisely that it was <em>not</em> my mother tongue, and that if it had been, then I wouldn&#39;t be able to hear it in anything like the same way I heard it <em>as an outsider.</em><br><br> Of course, over my six-plus decades of speaking French, I have become less and less of an outsider to it, but still I have somehow preserved the intense love that came from confronting the huge challenge of <em>making French my own</em> in my teenage years, as opposed to simply imbibing it like mother&#39;s milk, as a small child. And I am oh so proud of myself if, after half an hour&#39;s conversation, my native-French interlocutor is startled to learn that I did not grow up speaking French. By dint of intense concentration over decades, I&#39;ve <em>earned</em> that supreme compliment, and knowing I&#39;ve reached that long-dreamed-for level thanks to my years of really hard work is as great a feeling as any I have ever had.<br><br> Today&#39;s young people (even in Holland and Sweden) who grow up with translation software, however, will not be lured in the same way that I, as a teenager, was lured by the fantastic, surrealistic goal of internalizing another language. They won&#39;t feel the slightest temptation to devote a major fraction of their lives to slowly and arduously acquiring the sounds, vocabulary, grammar, and cultural richness of another language. To them, someone with my self-punishing attitude would seem hopelessly wedded to the past. Why on earth cling to riding a horse or a bicycle for transportation, when you can drive a car (not to mention flying in an airplane)? What&#39;s the point of going super slowly when you can go superfast? Okay, okay, on a horse or bicycle you&#39;ll see the scenery a bit better, but is it really worth it, when you can cross an entire continent in hours or days, instead of in weeks or months?<br><br> The question comes down to why we humans use language at all. Isn&#39;t the purpose of language just the communication of facts? If so, then why not simply go for maximizing the number of facts transferred per second? Well, to me, this sounds like a shockingly utilitarian and pragmatic description of what I view as a perpetually astonishing and quasi-magical phenomenon that lies at the very core of conscious life.<br><br> When I speak any language, as all my friends know well, I am always searching for the most appropriate word or idiom, frequently hesitating, stumbling, or suddenly changing course midstream; constantly joking by playing with ambiguity; having fun by putting on droll accents and personas, not to mention coming out with puns (some lovely, some lousy); using alliterative phrases; concocting new words on the fly; making accidental mistakes and laughing at myself; committing deliberate grammatical errors; unconsciously blending idioms and thus creating delightful new turns of phrase; tossing in words from other languages left and right; citing proverbs and quoting snippets of poetry; mixing metaphors; etc., etc. Speaking any language, for me, is a living, dynamic process that is permeated by my own unique humanness, with all its frailties and strengths. How is all of this wildly bubbling richness in Language A going to be mirrored in real time in Language B by a mechanical device that has nothing of those qualities driving it, that has no sense of humor, that has no understanding of irony or self-mockery, that has no awareness of how phrases are unconsciously blended, and so on?<br><br> For me, using language is the very essence of being human. When I speak, I am communicating not only <em>facts</em> , but a <em>way of being</em> . Through my word choices and subtle intonations and tiny hesitations and droll puns and dumb errors (and so on), I am revealing <em>who I am.</em> I am not a <em>persona</em> , but a <em>person</em> .<br><br> Today, though, it strikes me as possible—in fact, quite likely—that humans are collectively going to knuckle under and throw in the towel as far as foreign languages are concerned. Are we language users going to obsequiously hand over all engagement with other tongues to chatbots? Will young people in the coming decades share my youthful ardent desire to tackle towering linguistic Everests demanding long years of dedication? Or will they opt for the helicopter/chatbot pathway, preferring their linguistic lives to be struggle-free? If everything we might ever wish for is just handed to us gratis on a silver platter, then what, I wonder, is the purpose of living?<br><br> As my friend David Moser put it, what may soon go down the drain forever, thanks to these new AI technologies, is the precious gift that one can gain only by immersing oneself deeply in another culture and thereby acquiring an entirely new set of ways of looking at the world. It&#39;s a gift that can&#39;t help but turn any human being into a far richer and broader one. But David fears that it may soon become as rare as hen&#39;s teeth. And, I might add, David knows perfectly whereof he speaks, because in his 30s he recklessly threw himself into the bustling, boiling cauldron of China and its mysterious languages, and after long years of tenaciously clambering up its nearly vertical slopes (sorry for the mixed metaphor!), he emerged as a marvelously fluent speaker of Chinese, able to come out with breathtakingly witty puns on the fly and to do stand-up comedy on national television, not to mention hosting his own weekly TV show, in Chinese, about little-known facets of Beijing.<br><br> To Mo Dawei, as David is known in China, it&#39;s incredibly depressing to contemplate the profound impoverishment of people&#39;s mental and emotional lives that is looming just around every corner of the globe, thanks to the slick seductiveness of AI translation apps, insidiously creeping their way into ordinary people&#39;s lives and sapping their desire to make other tongues their own.<br><br> When children first hear the sounds of another language, they can&#39;t help but wonder: <em>What in the world would it feel like to speak that language?</em> Such eager childlike curiosity might seem universal and irrepressible. But what if that human curiosity is suddenly snuffed out forever by the onrushing tsunami of AI? When we collectively abandon the age-old challenge of learning the languages of other lands, when we relinquish that challenge to ultrarapid machines that have no inner life of their own but are able to give us fluent but fake facades in other languages, then we will have lost a major part of what it is to be human and alive.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 13 Jul 2023 13:56:56 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Four Ways to Make Grief More Bearable]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Losing a loved one inevitably brings pain. But how you respond not only affects your own healing but can also enable you to help others. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/L66U5adHHgNmsUnHWmYHeAd2GU4=/0x0:3000x1688/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/HowToBuildALife145/original.jpg" alt="An illustration of a weeping woman sniffing a happy bouquet." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Jan Buchczik</figcaption></figure> <i data-stringify-type="italic">Want to stay current with Arthur&#39;s writing? <a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/how-to-build-a-life/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/how-to-build-a-life/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up</a> to get an email every time a new column comes out.</i><br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">n 2010</span> , a Japanese garden designer named Itaru Sasaki, who was grieving the death of his cousin, created an unconnected telephone booth in which he had one-sided “conversations” with the dead relative. He found it comforting to do so. A year later, when the earthquake and tsunami that overwhelmed the Fukushima nuclear power plant killed almost 20,000 people in his country—including about 10 percent of the population of his own town—Sasaki opened his <i>kaze no denwa</i> , or “wind phone,” to the public. The booth has received more than 30,000 visitors to date, initially those who used it to “talk” with their family and friends who&#39;d been killed in the disaster but now almost anyone grieving the loss of a loved one, including tourists.<br><br> Grief can create a psychological, even physiological, disequilibrium so great that even a simulated phone connection can provide relief. And yet, grief is the most natural kind of suffering. We love others, and we will lose some of them. That&#39;s part of life: Given that nearly 3 million people die in the US every year, and each leaves, on average,<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/200995">an estimated five people bereaved</a> , almost 15 million Americans annually are experiencing fresh grief. Scholars believe that a more severe form, known as<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3384440/"> </a>prolonged grief, afflicts about one in 10 bereaved people a year; this describes a condition in which the mourner&#39;s suffering remains high over an extended period.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/03/finding-joy-happiness-in-absurd-boredom-stress/673248/">Arthur C. Brooks: How to find joy in your Sisyphean existence</a><br><br> Grief does not have to be a private misery and net harm to our lives. We can learn to comprehend it, manage it, and grow from it. And in understanding our own grief, we can help others heal and thrive as well.<br><br> W <span class="smallcaps">e often use</span> <i>bereavement</i> and <i>grief</i> synonymously, but they aren&#39;t the same. Bereavement is the experience of losing a loved one to death, whereas grief is the physical, psychological, and social response to that experience. This sort of sadness comes to every one of us, yet the experience is still shrouded in mystery. For many, the only thing they know about the science of grief is that it is thought to involve passing through five predictable stages—denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance. And this conventional wisdom, based on the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.psy.lmu.de/allg2/download/audriemmo/ws1011/kubler-ross.pdf">work</a> of the Swiss American psychiatrist Elisabeth Kübler-Ross and her colleagues dating from the late 1960s, has been largely abandoned by experts in recent decades.<br><br> Nevertheless, medical providers do <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://in.bgu.ac.il/en/fohs/communityhealth/Family/Documents/Complicated%20Grief.pdf">see</a> fairly common symptoms of grief, especially in the period right after a person learns of a loved one&#39;s death. The effects that typically occur are part of the “separation response,” which includes yearning, longing, and sadness but also commonly involves benign hallucinations of the loved one. This can also entail <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Thomas-Fuchs-6/publication/316013243_Presence_in_absence_The_ambiguous_phenomenology_of_grief/links/5a5b1414aca2727d60869f36/Presence-in-absence-The-ambiguous-phenomenology-of-grief.pdf">confusion</a> about your sense of self and of your relationship to others, if they emerged through deep intertwinement with the deceased, and even disorientation about what is past and present. For this reason, acute grief can resemble mild dementia, though of course it is not the same. Rather, the condition occurs because another person can be such a part of ourselves that when they disappear, we are temporarily destabilized in our sense of time and space.<br><br> Neuroscientists are learning about the brain&#39;s response to grief, which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24923337/">involves</a> (among other regions) activation of the anterior cingulate cortex, a part of the brain associated with the experience of pain, both physical and psychological. One way researchers measure physical arousal caused by grief is by how well the skin conducts electricity (known as “skin conductance response”), which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2695635/#:~:text=The%20skin%20conductance%20response%20(SCR)%20is%20an%20indirect%20measure%20of,emotional%20valence%20(Bradley%20et%20al.">indicates</a> the intensity of emotion and attention. Researchers of a small neuroanatomical study published in <i>The</i> <i>American Journal of Psychiatry</i> in 2003 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/doi/pdf/10.1176/appi.ajp.160.11.1946">reported</a> that this response was highest among the bereaved when grief-related words were accompanied by a photo of the deceased loved one, and much higher than if the subject was prompted by just one reminder or the other.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/12/breakup-heartbreak-moving-on-shorten-pain/672391/">Arthur C. Brooks: Breakups always hurt, but you can shorten the suffering</a><br><br> Given how debilitating grief can be, especially early on, it might seem like some sort of evolutionary glitch. Yet evolutionary biologists <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/culturing-science/the-evolution-of-grief-both-biological-and-cultural-in-the-21st-century/">believe</a> just the opposite. Staying close to kin was a survival imperative until relatively recently, so the pain of separation from someone very close was an important inducement to close that gap; failing to do so could mean dangerous isolation. Unfortunately, the death of a loved one means that that pain of separation cannot be relieved immediately and lessens only with time, as our brains become more accustomed to life without the person who has died.<br><br> For most people, that pain <i>does</i> decline with time. One way that researchers have measured this is by looking at the prevalence of depressive symptoms in successive months after the death of a loved one. One 2019 study of widowed women <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00127-019-01680-3">found</a> that depression was present in 38 percent within the first month; through the next two months, it was present in 25 percent; a year to a year and a half later, it was affecting 11 percent. Notably, there was a great deal of heterogeneity in the samples studied—everyone has a different experience of grief. Yet the data show that although people never forget their lost loved ones, most of the bereaved recover significantly in a matter of months.<br><br> A <span class="smallcaps">s difficult as</span> things can seem early on after the loss of a loved one, you can be happy again. In fact, a large body of research shows that over time, bereavement can even be an impetus for what psychologists <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Christina-Michael/publication/260244829_Post-traumatic_growth_following_bereavement_A_systematic_review_of_the_literature/links/00b495346ecbb5a1ca000000/Post-traumatic-growth-following-bereavement-A-systematic-review-of-the-literature.pdf">call</a> post-traumatic growth, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.apa.org/monitor/2016/11/growth-trauma">including</a> greater appreciation for life, improved relationships, recognition of new possibilities, personal strength, and spiritual development. Here are four ways to make grief more bearable early on, and to allow more pronounced growth down the line.<br><br> <strong>1. Look for meaning</strong><br> In the 1990s, researchers at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst interviewed college students who had recently lost a parent. The scholars asked the students about, among other things, their sense of meaning in the world: how just the world is, how random, how controllable. The researchers <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://guilfordjournals.com/doi/abs/10.1521/jscp.1991.10.3.270">found</a> that bereavement was significantly lower among the students who scored higher in their belief in a world with meaning. This suggests that a good course of action in a time of grief is to use the experience as an opportunity to ponder your beliefs and look for answers about life&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2021/10/meaning-life-macronutrients-purpose-search/620440/">coherence, purpose, and significance</a> . So it also makes sense that spiritual and religious progress are a common source of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2012-07744-001">growth</a> after bereavement.<br><br> <em>Want to hear more from Arthur C. Brooks? Join him and a selection of today&#39;s best writers and boldest voices at The Atlantic Festival on September 28 and 29. Get your pass <a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/live/atlantic-festival-2023/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/live/atlantic-festival-2023/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">here</a> .</em><br><br> <strong>2. Make changes to your identity</strong><br> When a loved one dies, that changes who you are—at a minimum in a purely factual way. For instance, the loss of a spouse means that you are now single. More than that, though, when you lose a loved one, it brings a change in your own identity, along with all sorts of behavioral changes. Single people, after all, do different things than married people. A 2013 review of older adults who&#39;d experienced bereavement <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0020748912004282?casa_token=ixKh7nfEbckAAAAA:mxhJe6tdeGKNDy6QWHsArhMuAaR3zLiq0Z-2vMaIV2RjpfH056FOq5rtEYe1wGF2DEIxRVFZlQ">found</a> that after they&#39;d lost someone, an essential factor of recovery included consciously embracing a new identity and making life changes. The lives they made involved going out more with friends, for example, or getting into new activities. Although grief is painful, it is also an opportunity to become a new person.<br><br> <strong>3. Adopt rituals</strong><br> One way of reestablishing a sense of control after the loss of a loved one is to create mourning rituals; even trivial-seeming ones can be effective. Researchers <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hbs.edu/ris/Publication%20Files/norton%20gino%202014_e44eb177-f8f4-4f0d-a458-625c1268b391.pdf">demonstrated</a> this in an experiment published in the <i>Journal of Experimental Psychology</i> in which people who had lost an important relationship through a breakup or death were asked to recall rituals related to the loss. For some, the rites were religious, such as sitting shiva; others played a favorite song on particular days or wrote letters to the loved one that they never sent. Those who remembered a ritual experienced 10 percent less grief than those who did not. When the researchers induced grief in a laboratory through randomly losing a lottery and then testing the impact of rituals in isolation regardless of belief, they found that these behaviors reduced grief intensity by 28 percent. The right practice for you will depend on your beliefs and circumstances, but it will help to do something systematic that acknowledges your loss and puts you in charge of your response.<br><br> <strong>4. Let yourself be happy again</strong><br> Specialists in the subject commonly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pathwayshealth.org/grief-support/is-it-ok-to-be-happy-during-grief/">point out</a> that grief can be accompanied by guilt when grief starts to subside, as if this were a signal that you didn&#39;t care so much after all about the person you lost. Similarly, people can feel a paradoxical sense of loss for the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/grace-in-grief/202303/can-you-be-happy-when-youre-decimated">grief</a> itself, as if the public longing for the lost one honored their connection to others too. Although grief is healthy and normal, it is important to remember that happiness is as well. We have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;id=Wzs0r4M5RncC&amp;oi=fnd&amp;pg=PA195&amp;dq=evolution+suffer+loss+of+loved+one&amp;ots=kukZp1zIMt&amp;sig=72pj2AkD2uxoP3TQHcjBL93mueI#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false">evolved</a> to suffer when separated from our loved ones, but not to suffer forever. Allow yourself to recover.<br><br> S <span class="smallcaps">o far</span> , I have been writing about one&#39;s own experience of grief and how to manage it. But what about another person who has had a loss and is suffering? We may struggle to help others in this situation, because the tendency is to avoid bereaved people when we don&#39;t know what to say or we think they want to be left alone. And perhaps their suffering frightens us. Grieving people <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1525/si.2008.31.4.422?casa_token=ntrhsxb0l6AAAAAA%3ARypM6HpoEPZWYvIlMaUfpxw0hX6TvkSG4vk7u09r4wlN4JiX80YTxane1UuBYRsiDgLKWBB0vm4OTu0">can also pull away</a> from us in an effort not to burden us with their sadness.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/10/five-stages-complicated-grief-wrong/671710/">Read: There are no &#39;five stages&#39; of grief</a><br><br> Avoiding those who are grieving is a mistake. Obviously, there are better and worse things to tell a person who has experienced a loss, and coming up with the right words might <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1525/si.2008.31.4.422?casa_token=ntrhsxb0l6AAAAAA%3ARypM6HpoEPZWYvIlMaUfpxw0hX6TvkSG4vk7u09r4wlN4JiX80YTxane1UuBYRsiDgLKWBB0vm4OTu0">reasonably worry you</a> . Many experts <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://rightasrain.uwmedicine.org/life/relationships/how-to-support-someone-grieving">suggest</a> that the best approach doesn&#39;t rely much on <i>your</i> words at all; it&#39;s best to simply be present and listen.<br><br> Just listening can be the best analgesic you can offer for the pain of others. It can even heal. As the psychologist Carl Rogers <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=ymS0e1jZmtMC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=%22a+way+of+being%22+carl+rogers&amp;hl=en&amp;newbks=1&amp;newbks_redir=0&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiNtND8m9f_AhUVFFkFHXj5AREQ6AF6BAgMEAI#v=onepage&amp;q=%22When%20I%20have%20been%20listened%20to%20and%20when%20I%20have%20been%20heard%2C%20I%20am%20able%20to%20re-perceive%20my%20world%20in%20a%20new%20way%20and%20to%20go%20on%22&amp;f=false">put</a> it, “When I have been listened to and when I have been heard, I am able to reperceive my world in a new way and to go on.”<br><br> The Japanese wind phone simulates a healing listener. Your attentive silence can be the real thing.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 13 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/grief-bereavement-loss-recovery/674675/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/grief-bereavement-loss-recovery/674675/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[When Will the Southwest Become Unlivable?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Air-conditioning and swimming pools are sustaining my community. I worry about the day when they won&#39;t be enough. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hbP4YkE-Xglj-SEoRg2n6rHOusk=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/summer_az/original.jpg" alt="儿童在室外游泳池游泳和玩耍的彩色照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Juan Arredondo / NYT / Redux</figcaption></figure> In the desert, summer starts in earnest in May. It&#39;s the beginning of dry season, with highs in the 90s—just a taste of the triple-digit days to come. Some people still venture out to trails and campsites, but for me, May marks the end of hiking season and the beginning of pool season. Every day since May 1, I&#39;ve been heading out for a swim at the University of Arizona recreation center, in Tucson, where I can watch the mourning doves and hawks crisscrossing the sky above me while I&#39;m doing the backstroke.<br><br> Four years ago, when my family was preparing to move to Tucson, I briefly fantasized about finding a home with a pool. Many small, middle-class houses in the city have them: cement holes in the ground flanked by even more cement. But my partner and I decided a backyard pool would use too much water in the desert, so instead, the university pool has become my lifeline.<br><br> Swimming is more than exercise. It&#39;s meditation, an escape from stress. In the desert, it can also be a necessity as summer temperatures rise and rise. Locals like to say that a couple of decades ago, we could count on finding respite from the heat: the occasional 90-degree high instead of 100, and cool nights to break up the sweltering days. But now the heat waves are ever present, and we must find refuge. Clouds and tree cover are rare, so our comfort and survival depend on man-made environments: movie theaters, museums, our air-conditioned homes, the pool.<br><br> This has always been a land of little rain and warm summers. But over the past two decades, chronic drought and heat have gotten steadily worse. This summer, a heat dome has parked over the Southwest; highs in Phoenix have hit 110 degrees for nearly two weeks straight. Arizona may be breaking records, but the trend is worldwide: On July 3, the average global temperature <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/05/world/hottest-day-world-climate-el-nino-intl/index.html">reached 62.62 degrees Fahrenheit</a> , the highest recorded since 1979. The next day was even hotter.<br><br> Each year, an average of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ephtracking.cdc.gov/Applications/heatTracker/">702 heat-related deaths</a> occur in the United States. Young children, older adults, and outdoor workers are among the most vulnerable. My family takes those deaths very seriously. We moved here in July 2019, and I decided I couldn&#39;t wait until fall to go on a hike, so we went. To this day, I remember the surge of anxiety I felt when I realized I&#39;d taken us deep into a trail in the middle of the day; there were no shade trees nearby, and our water was dwindling fast. Never again.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/10/heat-human-rights-issue-21st-century/616693/">Read: Heat is the human-rights issue of the 21st century</a><br><br> Those who have the means to adapt, do. Air-conditioning is absolutely necessary in Arizona. The summer we arrived, ours broke, and we found ourselves in the middle of a heat wave waiting a week to get it replaced because demand was so high. Our next-door neighbor lent us her swamp cooler—a device that cools air by evaporating water, and that many mobile-home residents depend on. Still, the sweltering temperatures kept us up at night that week.<br><br> Besides museums and pools, families take their kids to indoor gyms. The supermarket is a favorite place to hide from the heat. The city is running 20 free public pools this summer; businesses set up misters and umbrellas; there are new <em>raspados</em> (Mexican shaved-ice joints) popping up all over town. My neighborhood fire station has a big handwritten sign up front that I pass every time I go for a swim. Find shelter from the heat, it reads. All are welcome. The firehouse is one of several informal sites across the city; there are also six official ones. They&#39;re what you&#39;d imagine: big, air-conditioned rooms with places to sit, where water is readily available. For many older adults and houseless people, they can spell the difference between lethargy and vigor, or between life and death.<br><br> When I talk with friends in more temperate climates, many wonder how I could love living in the Sonoran Desert. I tell them that it&#39;s because this place has humbled me like nowhere else has, bringing me close to nature, to a slower and more sustainable pace of life. Here in Tucson, I&#39;ve met more people who are actively working on homegrown solutions to the climate crisis than I have in much bigger, better-resourced cities. Faced with unending heat, Tucsonans teach one another how to harvest rain, and advocate for bike-friendly infrastructure.<br><br> I think it&#39;s no coincidence that my fondness for desert life has grown at the same time that my adopted state has been forced to deal with more severe and frequent spells of extreme temperatures. The precarity of this life is exactly why I am so attached to it.<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/08/heat-index-model-climate-change/671152/">Read: America is going to have a &#39;Heat Belt&#39;</a><br><br> Millions and millions of Americans love the southwestern lifestyle. According to the latest census, Phoenix is now the fastest growing of all large American cities; its metro area recently surpassed 5 million people. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/mar/04/las-vegas-population-growth-climate-crisis">Las Vegas</a> , another water-strapped desert city, is growing disproportionately too.<br><br> Every new person who arrives is opting in to something beautiful—and every new person who arrives puts more strain on our limited refuges from the heat. I don&#39;t know when it will happen, but I worry about the day when the Sonoran Desert—and the wider Southwest—becomes unlivable because we won&#39;t have enough ways to keep cool. The escapes we have now may be available only to people in certain neighborhoods, likely those behind gates, with higher average incomes. Arizona is already limiting new construction around Phoenix for lack of groundwater.<br><br> In the next 30 years, according to an analysis by the climate nonprofit First Street Foundation, much of the US could experience <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://firststreet.org/press/press-release-2022-heat-model-launch/">temperatures</a> that the National Weather Service puts in its “extreme danger” category. Currently, about 8 million people are facing temperatures higher than 125 degrees Fahrenheit for days on end; by 2053, an estimated 107 million people will. Not all of them will be living in the Southwest, but the region will suffer. Climate experts <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-environment/2020/10/15/extreme-phoenix-heat-continue-worsen-weather-experts-say/3657637001/">are reluctant</a> to say whether this summer&#39;s extremes will become the norm, but they do predict that our region will keep breaking records.<br><br> And yet, despite these odds, people keep moving here. Maybe it&#39;s because we don&#39;t think of these extreme temperatures as a natural disaster. The change is happening gradually, albeit fast, year after year. Our bodies, so reliant on air-conditioning and pools, seem to be able to adjust, and come fall, our minds have a way of forgetting what a toll the heat took on us.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/south-extreme-heat-wave-texas-climate-change/674598/">Read: Summer in the South is becoming unbearable</a><br><br> Lately, I have been pondering all of this during my daily swims. I think about the privilege I have to be able to use a pool regularly, to move my body in the water, to be outside as temperatures keep rising. I imagine what not having access to any of that might feel like. And I wonder at what point a pool might be the last thing that sustains us here. What happens then? We can&#39;t just stay in the water 24 hours a day.<br><br> When my mind goes to those difficult places, I&#39;m prone to magical thinking. I tell myself that those of us who love the desert will figure things out together. The local government will step in. We still have time. And then, as I keep myself afloat and look up at the azure sky, I think about fall and winter, those cooler months that will take me back outdoors to the very reasons I love this place so much. To the reasons I want to stay.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 12 Jul 2023 22:30:46 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-dome-southwest-arizona/674689/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-dome-southwest-arizona/674689/</item></channel></rss>